\begin{abstract}
Standard long-only equity strategies leave institutional portfolios structurally vulnerable to severe market drawdowns and macroeconomic regime shifts. To harvest absolute returns orthogonal to traditional equity trend-following or valuation metrics, this paper provides a rigorous empirical analysis of the Variance Risk Premium (VRP) and the cross-sectional geometry of volatility futures. Replicating and expanding upon Bekaert \& Hoerova (2014) and Fassas \& Hourvouliades (2019), we construct a production-grade, out-of-sample systematic timing engine for S\&P 500 E-mini (ES) futures over the 2012--2026 window. We document a pervasive errors-in-variables attenuation bias when estimating Heterogeneous Autoregressive (HAR) panels via daily squared returns, noting a $4.2\times$ inflation in In-Sample Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE) entirely driven by realized variance proxy noise. While the variance swap (VS) strike offers an unbiased theoretical measure of risk-neutral expectations relative to the CBOE VIX index, both measures yield statistically indistinguishable out-of-sample predictive power for realized variance. In systematic execution, a univariate fixed-threshold VRP model delivers an out-of-sample Sharpe ratio of $1.024$ over 14 years, acting as a robust defensive filter. Crucially, we isolate a joint conditional regime transition during the 2020 COVID-19 crisis, where extreme market dislocations expanded predictor variance, collapsed Newey-West standard errors, and unlocked multi-factor trading channels. Incorporating a 5-day moving average of the VVIX index within an expanding-window framework with a rolling-mu threshold yields a Sharpe ratio of $0.981$ and slashes maximum drawdowns from $-30.2\%$ to $-12.2\%$. Finally, we detail the operational protocol for cross-asset robustness mapping onto Euro Stoxx 50 (V2X) and NASDAQ-100 arrays.
\end{abstract}

