\section{Introduction}
Institutional asset management frameworks are continuously challenged by the systemic vulnerabilities inherent in long-only equity strategies, which leave portfolios structurally exposed to catastrophic market liquidations, sudden macroeconomic regime adjustments, and tail-risk events. To construct absolute return engines capable of producing positive expected alpha over multi-week horizons, quantitative architectures must look beyond standard asset class beta, traditional momentum filters, or slow-moving fundamental valuation metrics. A compelling alternative lies in the deconstruction of options-implied metrics to isolate forward-looking measures of market risk aversion and uncertainty.

This paper focuses on the systemic exploitation of the Variance Risk Premium (VRP), defined mathematically as the spread between option-implied (risk-neutral) variance expectations and the unbiased statistical expectation of physical realized variance over a given forward horizon. In equilibrium macro-finance models, the VRP functions as a direct reflection of the economic compensation demanded by risk-averse market makers and institutional investors for underwriting volatility risk, specifically relating to non-Gaussian compound-Poisson jump shocks and transient regime uncertainty under a preference for the early resolution of anxiety (Drechsler \& Yaron, 2011). Because equity options fundamentally behave as financial insurance policies, their implied volatility index level typically overstates the actual price fluctuations that eventually occur over the lifetime of the option contracts. During acute market sell-offs, extreme institutional panic causes these option premiums to dramatically overshoot reality. This premium contains robust predictive information for subsequent equity index returns over multi-week horizons as excessive anxieties mean-revert and settle back toward historical baselines.

The scope of this research is strictly confined to the engineering of an equity index futures timing engine, specifically targeting the highly liquid S\&P 500 E-mini (ES) front-month futures contract. Crucially, the strategy's universe uses signals embedded within volatility index levels, futures curves, and variance swap markets solely to determine direction and leverage sizing, completely avoiding direct execution or placement within volatility instruments themselves (e.g., VIX options, VIX futures, or exchange-traded products). 

This report details the systematic realization of this framework across five core dimensions:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item A baseline replication of the foundational HAR-RV-VIX predictive panel from Bekaert \& Hoerova (2014) to isolate the data-substitution penalties encountered when moving from 5-minute intraday records to daily end-of-day squared return arrays.
    \item A cross-sectional linear geometry model of the VIX futures curve following Fassas \& Hourvouliades (2019) to quantify long-term vs. short-term volatility expectations.
    \item The development of a production-grade, day-by-day rolling extraction loop with automated monthly predictive diagnostics and diagnostic kill switches.
    \item A systematic multi-signal timing engine tested out-of-sample from 2012 to 2026, evaluating symmetric, rolling-mu, and excess return thresholds alongside multi-level leverage allocation rules.
    \item An investigation of the regime-conditional evolution of signal significance, examining the structural impact of the 2020 COVID-19 crisis, alongside a framework for cross-asset transmission into European and technology-concentrated equity benchmarks.
\end{enumerate}

\section{Past Literature and Baseline Replications}
The literature surrounding volatility-derived equity predictability follows two separate paths: the estimation of time-varying variance premiums in the time series, and the extraction of term structure shape metrics in the cross-section.

\subsection{Time-Series Predictability and the HAR Framework}
Bekaert \& Hoerova (2014) established that when option-implied metrics are rigorously deconstructed, the isolated VRP component cleanly predicts future equity risk premiums, whereas the physical conditional variance component captures distinct channels of real macroeconomic contraction and banking-sector financial instability. The gold standard for modeling the physical component is the Heterogeneous Autoregressive (HAR) framework popularized by Corsi (2009), which successfully captures the long-memory properties of financial volatility by formalizing a cascade of daily, weekly, and monthly trading horizons. These horizons represent the distinct holding periods and reaction speeds of speculative day-traders, rebalancing institutional managers, and structural macroeconomic allocators.

However, a core constraint of the Bekaert \& Hoerova (2014) framework is its heavy reliance on high-frequency, 5-minute intraday tick data to construct the realized variance (RV) series. In operational environments where high-frequency intraday data may be missing, irregular, or distorted by microstructural frictions, investigators must substitute high-frequency arrays with daily end-of-day squared returns. This data substitution introduces an explicit errors-in-variables problem, as a single daily squared return possesses roughly $252\times$ higher estimation variance than a 5-minute intraday RV measure that aggregates 78 clean intraday squared returns per session. 

\subsection{Cross-Sectional Slope Dynamics}
Separately, Fassas \& Hourvouliades (2019) and Simon \& Campasano (2014) examined the predictive edge contained within the cross-sectional geometry of the VIX futures curve. Empirical studies demonstrate that the volatility curve exhibits a highly asymmetric characteristic: volatility curve inversion (backwardation) operates as a powerful contrarian buy indicator for underlying equities by successfully capturing sharp relief rallies as spot volatility mean-reverts downward. Conversely, standard upward-sloping curves (contango) offer minimal predictive information for positive equity returns. Short-tenor volatility futures are known to be structurally overpriced relative to subsequent ex-post spot index movements—a forecast bias driven heavily by massive, inelastic capital inflows into long-only retail volatility exchange-traded products (ETPs) that mechanically buy front-month futures contracts regardless of fair economic value (Asensio, 2013).

\subsection{Replication Pitfalls and Adopted Innovations}
Direct application of these concepts into a production engine introduces major systematic frictions:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Regime Inactivity:} Because the volatility futures curve resides in contango roughly $75\%$ to $83\%$ of the time, slope-based contrarian long signals are highly episodic, leaving multi-factor strategies completely inactive or flat during extended bull market regimes.
    \item \textbf{Friction Sensitivity:} Short-horizon basis and roll-capture trading models exhibit extreme sensitivity to bid-ask spreads, execution delays, and roll-cost assumptions.
    \item \textbf{Asymmetric Tail Risk:} Harvesting the variance risk premium is mathematically equivalent to selling tail-risk insurance, exposing unconstrained portfolios to catastrophic drawdowns during sudden, non-linear market drops.
\end{itemize}

To mitigate these limitations, our experiment adopts the HAR-RV cascade from Bekaert \& Hoerova (2014) to model physical expectations, integrates the daily cross-sectional OLS slope extraction from Fassas \& Hourvouliades (2019), and overlays a strict Newey-West standard error t-statistic gate. This gate acts as a dynamic regime filter, forcing the model into cash or flat states when the underlying parameters fail to exhibit acceptable statistical significance.

\section{Methodology}

\subsection{Data Specifications and Storage Infrastructure}
The quantitative infrastructure integrates several disparate data streams across a historical window spanning from January 3, 1990, through February 27, 2026. The dataset contains a total of $n = 4,359$ observations for the variance swap estimation sample, and over $5,500$ trading days for the VIX futures cross-sectional analysis. Daily closing values for the CBOE Volatility Index (VIX) and the CBOE VIX-of-VIX Index (VVIX) are sourced from \texttt{VolatilityIndexData.csv}. Daily risk-neutral implied variance streams are derived from \texttt{EquityIndexVarianceSwapData.csv}, filtered specifically to the underlying ticker symbol \texttt{'SPX'} and a maturity tenor of exactly 1.0 month (\texttt{TENOR\_MONTHS=1.0}). Physical return data for the underlying equity index are captured from the front-month E-mini S\&P 500 (ES) futures contract stored in \texttt{EquityFuture\_historical.parquet}.

\subsection{Extraction of the Variance Risk Premium}
The premium extraction protocol is conducted through an 8-step production pipeline engineered to insulate the output vector from look-ahead contamination.

\paragraph{Step 1: Implied Variance Quantification.} Two distinct risk-neutral variance streams are managed in parallel. For the full historical sample, the VIX-based implied variance is scaled to a monthly basis:
\begin{equation}
IVar_{\text{VIX}, t} = \frac{\text{VIX}_t^2}{12}
\end{equation}
For the post-November 2008 sample, the theoretically exact, model-free variance swap fair strike is utilized:
\begin{equation}
IVar_{\text{VS}, t} = \frac{\text{VS}_t^2}{12}
\end{equation}
The VIX calculation suffers from a known convexity bias due to the log-contract replication integral and truncation across a finite strike range, creating a persistent upward level shift relative to the exact variance swap strike.

\paragraph{Step 2: Physical Realized Variance Multi-Frequency Deconstruction.} The physical realized variance components are extracted from the daily log returns $r_t$ of the front-month ES contract, scaled to percentage units, and projected to monthly horizons ($22$ trading days):
\begin{equation}
RV_t^{(1)} = (r_t \times 100)^2 \times 22
\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
RV_t^{(5)} = \left[ \frac{1}{5}\sum_{k=0}^{4} (r_{t-k} \times 100)^2 \right] \times 22
\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
RV_t^{(22)} = \sum_{k=0}^{21} (r_{t-k} \times 100)^2
\end{equation}

\paragraph{Step 3: Corsi Heterogeneous Autoregressive Model Fitting.} The conditional expectation of physical realized variance $\mathbb{E}^\mathbb{P}[RV_{t+1}^{(22)} \mid \mathcal{F}_t]$, denoted as $CV_t$, is generated via an ordinary least squares (OLS) panel regression with a 44-lag Newey-West Heterogeneous and Autocorrelation Consistent (HAC) covariance adjustment to account for the overlapping structure of the monthly target window:
\begin{equation}
RV_{t+1}^{(22)} = c + \alpha \cdot \frac{X_t^2}{12} + \beta^m \cdot RV_t^{(22)} + \beta^w \cdot RV_t^{(5)} + \beta^d \cdot RV_t^{(1)} + \epsilon_t
\end{equation}

\paragraph{Step 4: Variance Risk Premium Isolation.} The continuous premium vector ($VP_t$) is isolated by subtracting the conditional physical expectation from the concurrent risk-neutral measure:
\begin{equation}
VP_t = IVar_t - CV_t
\end{equation}

\paragraph{Step 5: End-of-Day Production Loop (Rolling vs. Expanding).} To ensure live viability, the parameters are updated dynamically. Under the 500-day rolling loop, the HAR model is refitted daily on a historical block spanning from $[t-500, t-1]$. To entirely eliminate look-ahead contamination, a strict 22-day gap is maintained between the youngest available training label $RV_{t-21}^{(22)}$ and the active prediction date $t$. Under the expanding protocol, the training anchor is fixed at January 2, 1990, and the sample grows by one row per day.

\paragraph{Step 6: Real-Time Predictive Diagnostics and Kill Switches.} At the final trading session of each calendar month, an automated verification script runs an out-of-sample Mincer-Zarnowitz tracking regression:
\begin{equation}
RV_{\text{actual}, t+22}^{(22)} = a + b \cdot CV_t + \eta_t
\end{equation}
The system calculates the Diebold-Mariano (DM) test statistic relative to a simple persistence martingale baseline. If the slope coefficient $b$ shifts beyond a 95\% confidence threshold ($|b - 1| / \text{SE} > 1.96$) or the DM p-value exceeds $0.05$, a real-time kill switch suspends the strategy, defaulting the allocation to cash.

\paragraph{Step 7: Statistical Accuracy Evaluation.} Out-of-sample predictive precision is continually benchmarked against the Martingale persistence model ($\mathbb{E}[RV_{t+22}] = RV_t^{(22)}$) via Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE), Mean Absolute Error (MAE), and Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE).

\paragraph{Step 8: Mincer-Zarnowitz R² Scale Isolation.} The scale-free accuracy of the predictive tracking vector is isolated via the $MZ\text{-}R^2$ coefficient from Equation 8, confirming the ranking capacity of the premium extract.

\subsection{VIX Term Structure Geometry Fitting}
On each trading day $t$, the cross-sectional geometry of the volatility curve is parameterized by mapping all listed VIX futures contract prices ($price_{i,t}$) against their respective annualized time-to-maturity ($TtM_{i,t} = \text{days to last trade} / 365.25$). A minimum filtering threshold requires at least 3 active contracts per session:
\begin{equation}
price_{i,t} = \alpha_{0,t} + \beta_{0,t} \cdot TtM_{i,t} + \varepsilon_{i,t}
\end{equation}
The cross-sectional slope coefficient ($\beta_{0,t}$) serves as our structural curve signal, where $\beta_{0,t} > 0$ denotes a standard contango regime and $\beta_{0,t} < 0$ defines an acute backwardation stress state.

\subsection{Central Return Regression Framework}
To establish the multi-factor equity timing engine, the forward 20-calendar-day cumulative return of the front-month ES contract is formalized as the dependent target variable:
\begin{equation}
fwd\_ret_{20, t} = \left[ \prod_{k=1}^{20} (1 + \text{daily\_ret}_{t+k}) \right] - 1
\end{equation}
We specify seven separate linear and non-linear predictive configurations evaluated via an expanding-window OLS protocol with a 20-lag Newey-West HAC correction:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Base Model (Univariate VRP):}
    \begin{equation}
    fwd\_ret_{20, t} = c + \beta_1 \cdot VRP_t + \epsilon_t
    \end{equation}
    \item \textbf{Model A (Bivariate VRP + Term Slope):}
    \begin{equation}
    fwd\_ret_{20, t} = c + \beta_1 \cdot VRP_t + \beta_2 \cdot \beta_{0,t} + \epsilon_t
    \end{equation}
    \item \textbf{Model B (Bivariate VRP + Equity Trend Quotient):} Parameterized via the ratio of the spot ES price to its 200-day simple moving average ($TQ_t = P_t / \text{SMA}_{200}(P_t)$):
    \begin{equation}
    fwd\_ret_{20, t} = c + \beta_1 \cdot VRP_t + \beta_2 \cdot TQ_t + \epsilon_t
    \end{equation}
    \item \textbf{Model C (Bivariate VRP + Volatility Uncertainty):} Integrated via the 5-day moving average of the VVIX index scaled to monthly units ($VVIX_{\text{MA5}, t} = [ \frac{1}{5}\sum_{k=0}^{4} \text{VVIX}_{t-k} ] / \sqrt{12}$):
    \begin{equation}
    fwd\_ret_{20, t} = c + \beta_1 \cdot VRP_t + \beta_2 \cdot VVIX_{\text{MA5}, t} + \epsilon_t
    \end{equation}
    \item \textbf{Model G (Interaction Framework):}
    \begin{equation}
    fwd\_ret_{20, t} = c + \beta_1 \cdot (VRP_t \times VVIX_{\text{MA5}, t}) + \epsilon_t
    \end{equation}
    \item \textbf{Model H (Asymmetric Structural Split):} Decomposing the premium into positive and negative vector regimes:
    \begin{equation}
    fwd\_ret_{20, t} = c + \beta_1 \cdot \max(VRP_t, 0) + \beta_2 \cdot \min(VRP_t, 0) + \epsilon_t
    \end{equation}
    \item \textbf{Model VRP+OI (Microstructural Demand):} Incorporating the total front-month ES open interest, smoothed via a 252-day backward moving average ($OI_t$) to strip out quarterly roll teeth:
    \begin{equation}
    fwd\_ret_{20, t} = c + \beta_1 \cdot VRP_t + \beta_2 \cdot OI_t + \epsilon_t
    \end{equation}
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Algorithmic Logic Gate and Position Sizing Protocol}
At each daily execution interval $i$ across the out-of-sample trading window (spanning January 1, 2012, through January 27, 2026), the system ingests data strictly from a training slice defined by $\text{panel.iloc}[0 : i-20]$. This strict 20-day gap forces the most recent training label $fwd\_ret_{20, i-21}$ to be completely realized before generating prediction $\hat{y}_i$, eliminating overlapping look-ahead leakage.

An active position is taken only if the model passes a strict Newey-West t-statistic gate. Specifically, the absolute t-statistics for ALL non-intercept coefficients must exceed $|t| > 1.28$, representing an 80\% one-sided confidence threshold. If any individual predictor fails this hurdle, the active position for that specific model is forced to zero ($pos_i = 0$).

We evaluate three alpha threshold execution variations across a comprehensive delta mesh where $\delta \in \{0.2\%, 0.5\%, 0.75\%, 1.0\%\}$:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Symmetric Fixed Threshold (EW Fixed):}
    \begin{equation}
    pos_i = 
    \begin{cases} 
    +1 & \text{if } \hat{y}_i > +\delta \\ 
    -1 & \text{if } \hat{y}_i < -\delta \\ 
    0 & \text{otherwise} 
    \end{cases}
    \end{equation}
    \item \textbf{Rolling-Mu Threshold (EW Rolling-Mu):} Benchmarking predictions against the trailing 500-day mean of realized 20-day equity returns ($\mu_i$):
    \begin{equation}
    pos_i = 
    \begin{cases} 
    +1 & \text{if } \hat{y}_i > \mu_i + \delta \\ 
    -1 & \text{if } \hat{y}_i < \mu_i - \delta \\ 
    0 & \text{otherwise} 
    \end{cases}
    \end{equation}
    \item \textbf{Excess Return Shift Framework:} Shifting the dependent target variable directly during the in-sample regression phase by subtracting the long-run equity premium ($y_{\text{excess}, t} = fwd\_ret_{20, t} - 0.9444\%$, where $0.9444\%$ represents an annualized equity premium of $11.9\%$ scaled to a 20-day window). The symmetric fixed threshold rule from Equation 18 is then applied directly to the excess return prediction $\hat{y}_{\text{excess}, i}$.
\end{enumerate}

To scale the strategy based on signal conviction, we introduce an unbound, multi-level \textbf{Leveraged Sizing Strategy} executed within \texttt{leveraged\_strategies.py}. Instead of binary $\pm1$ allocations, gross leverage is mapped dynamically as a continuous function of alpha strength across the threshold boundaries:
\begin{equation}
pos_{\text{leveraged}, i} = 
\begin{cases} 
\pm 4 & \text{if } |\text{excess}_i| \ge 1.0\% \\ 
\pm 3 & \text{if } |\text{excess}_i| \ge 0.75\% \\ 
\pm 2 & \text{if } |\text{excess}_i| \ge 0.5\% \\ 
\pm 1 & \text{if } |\text{excess}_i| \ge 0.2\% \\ 
0 & \text{if } |\text{excess}_i| < 0.2\% \text{ or t-gate fails} 
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\subsection{Backtest Evaluation Parameters and Frictional Adjustments}
Portfolio simulation assumes full capital allocation to the active ES position, incorporating a strict transaction cost haircut of $0.05\%$ per trade applied directly to changes in position size ($|\Delta pos_t|$). To avoid penalizing direct cross-over flips, a complete reversal from long to short ($+1 \rightarrow -1$) is treated as a single structural trade and capped at a maximum friction cost of $0.05\%$ per day. 

Risk statistics incorporate an annualized risk-free rate of $3\%$ directly into the Sharpe ratio denominator:
\begin{equation}
\text{Sharpe} = \frac{\text{Ann. Return} - 0.03}{\text{Ann. Volatility}}
\end{equation}
Simulated metrics do not credit the portfolio with the interest earned on unreserved capital or margin deposits, which represents a conservative baseline.

\subsection{Regime Transition to European and Cross-Asset Benchmarks}
To test for geographic and microstructural signal decay, Experiment 3 establishes a rigid validation framework. The \textbf{European Equity Track} ingests daily closing levels, physical variance records, V2X futures curves, and the VV2X index from the Euro Stoxx 50 ecosystem. It applies the identical HAR filtering panel and bivariate timing logic to determine whether the isolated VRP is an invariant feature of mature equity markets or a phenomenon confined to US equity market structures. Concurrently, the \textbf{Cross-Asset Domestic Track} maps the broad-market S\&P 500 VRP and VIX term structure metrics directly onto the technology-concentrated NASDAQ-100 index (NDX) to isolate cross-asset lead-lag transmission dynamics and determine whether broad-market sentiment effectively times sector-concentrated growth assets.

