\subsection{Deep-Dive Performance and Behavioral Analysis}
The empirical results compiled in Table~\tabref{tab:backtest_results} expose critical structural features across the different model specifications:

\paragraph{1. The Robustness of Univariate Fixed VRP.} The \textbf{Base Model (EW Fixed, $\delta = 0.2\%$)} delivers the strongest overall performance, achieving an out-of-sample Sharpe ratio of $\textbf{1.024}$ versus the passive buy-and-hold benchmark of $0.856$. This strategy maintains a $99\%$ long allocation vector and generates $0\%$ short signals, as raw VRP predictions rarely cross below negative symmetric thresholds. The performance edge is defensive: it avoids major downside velocity during high-uncertainty environments (shrinking maximum drawdowns from $-30.2\%$ to $-26.4\%$) while capturing an additional $+2.52\%$ in annualized net return. Because this strategy maintains active exposure across the entire 14-year backtest, it represents our most statistically robust result.

\paragraph{2. The Destructive Nature of Rolling-Mu on Structural Biases.} Applying the rolling-mu adjustment to the Base Model destroys its performance, crashing the Sharpe ratio from $1.024$ down to $\textbf{0.186}$. Because the VRP is structurally positive on $66\%$ of all days, the rolling-mu framework misinterprets positive premium readings as ``below-average'' relative to recent trailing equity growth. This generates false short signals ($12\%$ short allocation) that fight the long-term equity risk premium.

\paragraph{3. The Tail-Risk Mitigating Power of Rolling-Mu Model C.} Conversely, the rolling-mu configuration works exceptionally well when applied to \textbf{Model C (VRP + VVIX MA5)}, driving the Sharpe ratio to $\textbf{0.981}$ and shrinking the maximum drawdown to $\textbf{-12.2\%}$ (compared to $-30.2\%$ for buy-and-hold). This occurs because VVIX operates as a high-information, two-sided market stress indicator. High VVIX levels successfully predict below-average forward equity returns relative to the trailing mean, while low VVIX levels predict outperformance. Isolating the VVIX component within a univariate \textbf{Model VVIX (Rolling-Mu, $\delta=0.5\%$)} yields a comparable Sharpe ratio of $\textbf{0.958}$ and a maximum drawdown of $\textbf{-11.5\%}$, proving that the predictive power of Model C is heavily dominated by the VVIX term. Standardized coefficient analysis confirms this dominance: $\beta_{\text{VVIX}} \times \sigma(\text{VVIX}) \approx 0.50\%$ per 20 days, whereas $\beta_{\text{VRP}} \times \sigma(\text{VRP}) \approx 0.19\%$.

\paragraph{4. Structural Parameter Neutralization in Model B.} Model B represents a total systematic failure, remaining $\textbf{100\%}$ flat across the entire backtest history. The rolling in-sample t-statistic for the 200-day moving average trend quotient continuously hovers around its full-sample estimate of $-0.53$, failing to clear the joint t-statistic gate threshold of $|t| > 1.28$ at any single execution date.

\paragraph{5. Open Interest Demand Reinforcement.} The \textbf{Model VRP+OI (EW Fixed, $\delta=0.5\%$)} configuration delivers a strong Sharpe ratio of $\textbf{0.966}$, maintaining a high $91\%$ long exposure and a minimal $2\%$ short profile. The rolling t-statistic for open interest regularly clears the gate alongside VRP, demonstrating that rising open interest acts as a structural volume validation signal that reinforces the premium allocation.

\subsection{Coefficient Significance Evolution and the 2020 t-Gate Lockout}
Tracking the evolution of the rolling Newey-West t-statistics over the 2012--2026 window exposes a clear regime-conditional pattern. Throughout the \textbf{2012--2019 sub-period} (characterized by low macro volatility and a persistent equity bull market), the rolling t-statistics for the VIX term slope (Model A) and the VVIX moving average (Model C) regularly failed to clear the $|t| > 1.28$ hurdle. As a direct consequence, Model A and Model C remained flat or cash-allocated for nearly eight years, missing the entire pre-pandemic equity advance.

The structural mechanism driving this lockout relates directly to the mathematical structure of the Newey-West standard error estimate:
\begin{equation}
t(\hat{\beta}_j) \approx \frac{\hat{\beta}_j \times \sigma(x_j) \times \sqrt{n}}{\sigma_\varepsilon}
\end{equation}
During the calm 2012--2019 regime, both the VIX futures slope and the VVIX index fluctuated within exceptionally narrow bands, resulting in a small independent predictor variance $\sigma(x_j)$. This variance restriction inflated the standard error bounds and suppressed the t-statistic values below the gate threshold. 

The strategy experienced a major structural regime shift during the \textbf{March 2020 COVID-19 crisis}. The extreme market dislocations introduced unprecedented volatility data points: the VIX futures curve collapsed into extreme backwardation before reverting to record contango, and the VVIX index spiked past $200$. These massive historical observations expanded the running calculation of $\sigma(x_j)$ and collapsed the standard error bounds. This structural shift pushed the rolling t-statistics past the $|t| > 1.28$ threshold, unlocking active trading states for Models A, C, and VVIX. Consequently, their active out-of-sample track records are effectively confined to a 5-year post-2020 regime (2020--2026), whereas the Base VRP model maintains continuous operational validity across the full 14-year window.

\subsection{Leveraged Portfolio Multi-Level Allocation Matrix}
When multi-level leverage allocation rules are applied through \texttt{leveraged\_strategies.py}, the asymmetric and rolling-mu variants generate substantial return expansion. This pattern confirms that the magnitude of our forward alpha predictions is as informative as the underlying directional sign. The \textbf{Leveraged Asymmetric Model C (VRP+VVIX)} configuration achieves global risk-adjusted outperformance across the expanded backtest mesh, delivering an annualized Sharpe ratio of $\textbf{+1.672}$. It is closely supported by the \textbf{Leveraged Base-Return-Shift VRP+VIX MA10} model, which secures an optimized Sharpe ratio of $\textbf{+1.882}$, validating the capacity of unbound scaling to amplify performance when backed by robust statistical significance gates.

\section{Conclusion and Further Research Directions}

\subsection{Deployment Recommendations}
Based on the empirical results, we present two distinct deployment recommendations depending on institutional mandate:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Core Alpha Sizing (Base VRP Fixed, $\delta=0.2\%$):} Recommended as a permanent overlay for broad equity timing. It provides a 14-year out-of-sample Sharpe ratio of $1.024$ and boasts complete regime robustness across both low-volatility and high-volatility environments.
    \item \textbf{Tail-Risk Mandated Tactical Sizing (Model C Rolling-Mu, $\delta=0.2\%$):} Recommended for portfolios with tight drawdown limits. By using the two-sided signaling properties of the VVIX index, this model cuts maximum drawdowns to $-12.2\%$, providing exceptional downside protection during high-velocity liquidations.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Identified Systematic Frictions and Limitations}
Operational implementation must account for three core structural constraints:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Proxy Attenuation Constraints:} Relying on daily end-of-day returns introduces an explicit errors-in-variables degradation, inflating residual variance by $4.2\times$ and lowering the out-of-sample $MZ\text{-}R^2$ compared to high-frequency intraday alternatives.
    \item \textbf{Regime Lockout Vulnerability:} Multi-factor specifications (incorporating term structure slope and VVIX) are highly regime-conditional. They risk entering extended multi-year flat states when predictor variance narrows, trailing simple buy-and-hold benchmarks during stable bull markets.
    \item \textbf{Implicit Option-Selling Profile:} Strategies driven by the VRP inherit the structural risks of tail-insurance underwriting. Unconstrained leverage scaling exposes the portfolio to severe drawdown risk during non-linear market gap events that violate linear OLS parameters.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Avenues for Future Empirical Inquiry}
Following the analytical framework established in our research presentation, four critical questions warrant further investigation:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Non-Linear VRP Modeling via Machine Learning:} Given that the Corsi HAR panel is a linear model, future research should replace OLS frameworks with localized non-linear extraction models (e.g., Random Forests, Gradient Boosted Regressors, or LSTM networks) to test whether non-linear parameters better capture rapid volatility regime shifts.
    \item \textbf{Noise Correlation Dynamics between VRP and VVIX:} While VRP and VVIX exhibit minimal linear correlation, they may share complex, non-linear noise structures. Resolving this interaction could clarify why their multi-factor combination provides superior drawdown management.
    \item \textbf{Microstructural Triggers Across Stress Regimes:} Future research should investigate why the VVIX index behaves differently across separate crisis episodes—specifically contrasting its signaling characteristics during the 2008 Global Financial Crisis against the 2020 COVID-19 shock.
    \item \textbf{Signal Decay Under Macroeconomic Shifts:} Investigators must monitor whether the predictive power of the VVIX signal undergoes long-term decay as structural retail capital shifts across the volatility ETP ecosystem, ensuring the strategy retains its structural edge.
\end{enumerate}

